data.content:
Here's the mapping:

| NUnit | xUnit equivalent |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` | **Constructor** |
| `[TearDown]` | **`IDisposable.Dispose`** |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` / `[OneTimeTearDown]` | **`IClassFixture<T>`** with a shared fixture class |

Converted code:

```csharp
// Shared fixture replaces [OneTimeSetUp] / [OneTimeTearDown]
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests
    : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor replaces [SetUp] — runs before each test
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // Dispose replaces [TearDown] — runs after each test
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key points:
- **`IClassFixture<T>`** — xUnit creates `DatabaseFixture` once and shares it across all tests in the class. The fixture's `Dispose` runs after all tests complete.
- **Constructor/`IDisposable`** — xUnit creates a **new class instance per test**, so the constructor and `Dispose` naturally act as per-test setup/teardown.
- The fixture is injected via the constructor parameter (`DatabaseFixture _`) even if you don't need to reference it directly.
